SIMPLE: ephemeris
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ephemeris
<hw>E*phem"e*ris</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Ephemerides</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., a diary, Gr. <?/,
also, a calendar, fr. <?/. See <er>Ephemera</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A diary; a journal.</def> <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A publication giving
the computed places of the heavenly bodies for each day of the year,
with other numerical data, for the use of the astronomer and navigator;
an astronomical almanac; <as>as, the ⟦ldquo⟧American <ex>Ephemeris</ex>
and Nautical Almanac</as>.⟦rdquo⟧</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any tabular
statement of the assigned places of a heavenly body, as a planet or
comet, on several successive days.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Literature)</fld> <def>A collective name for
reviews, magazines, and all kinds of periodical literature.</def>
<rj><au>Brande & C.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ephemerist</ent>⟦br⟧
